Consider how Christians were once persecuted, shunned, and killed by the Roman Empire, only to later have that empire become Christian. Our country has progressed from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The coming great reversal in Christian history will unfold, undoing history in search of its source and reversing diversity in the process. An important factor in making this possible will be interpreting Jesus' words metaphorically, not literally. So, what transpired since Jesus' lifetime?

If we delve deeply into history, we find only Judaism as the theological origin of Christianity. Monotheism, divine revelation, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were central to the religion by the time the Romans conquered Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish population was not united in spirit. They split into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and the majority of common people.

I reckon The Jungle demonstrates that people, deep down, are inherently selfish and self-serving. They strive to make their lives the best they can without concerning themselves with those less fortunate. The novel underscores this through the owners and managers of the colossal factories. Their sole aim is to expand their empires, disregarding any obstacle, whether it's people or creatures, that might impede their progress. As Upton Sinclair writes, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." This vivid imagery conveys the immense damage the pollution is causing, while highlighting the owners' callous disregard for anyone or anything harmed by their pursuits. They couldn't care less about the suffocating smoke pouring from the factories or the waste from the countless pens around Packingtown. Their apathy extends to their employees, whom they exploit mercilessly to increase profits. "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar." They subject workers to grueling hours and summarily dismiss them without compensation or job assistance, all while safety regulations were virtually nonexistent. Consequently, the hardships faced by those who perished in Packingtown were accepted as the norm, with no recourse or assistance available. Unions, intended to aid the workers, often ended up exploiting them further. The workers found themselves trapped in a system akin to slavery, forced into terrible living and working conditions, with no way out. As Sinclair eloquently puts it, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Many creators employ various methods to evoke specific feelings or attitudes in their readers towards significant themes. Some of these strategies are more potent than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald utilizes numerous techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, Fitzgerald combines an adjective with a noun in an unconventional way to create a certain ambiance around a subject. Other times, he assigns meaning to a symbol and then employs it for the same purpose. Fitzgerald employs this latter technique with several colors, including gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. In his novel, Fitzgerald builds up connotations for these colors, particularly white/gray and red/pink, which he later uses to evoke feelings around important objects.

Fitzgerald assigns a meaning to white/gray, with white representing a higher class and gray symbolizing age and fadedness. He establishes this meaning early in the novel through repeated references to both colors. Daisy and Jordan are consistently "in white" (8), with everyone else wearing white, such as Nick in "white flannels" (41) at Gatsby's party, Tom in a "white shirt" (36) during his meeting with Myrtle, and Catherine in "powdered milky white" (30). The only deviation is when Nick observes Gatsby's party: "the halls... are gaudy with primary colors" (40). Fitzgerald further reinforces these colors by assigning them to mundane subjects: Nick's commute takes him "down the white chasms of lower New York" (56), the names of guests at Gatsby's parties are "gray names" (61) on Nick's schedule, Catherine's apartment is a "slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses," and plain or common people and places are described as white or gray, such as Jordan and Daisy's "white girlhood" (19) together, the "gray cars" and "gray land" (23) in the valley of ashes, the "gray Italian child" on the train (26), and the dog-seller, a "gray old man" (27).

Once Fitzgerald infuses white/gray with sufficient meaning, he uses these colors to signify insignificance or uniformity around certain subjects. This technique begins with Daisy. After a prolonged absence of these colors, Fitzgerald describes Daisy as "dressed in white" in "a little white roadster," making her seem less of a character and more like a uniform addition, something Gatsby desires and yearns for (74). Fitzgerald continues this technique around Daisy to convey her uniformity, such as the "gray haze of Daisy's fur collar" (18), and her appearance in a "white" (115) dress before Tom and Gatsby's encounter.

San Diego County is a farming powerhouse, thanks to its mild, sunny climate. Common crops here are tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There's a thriving market for organic, community-supported agriculture in the area, with long waiting lists for local organizations. Organic eggs and milk are also in demand. Many organic farms offer tours and recreational activities like hiking and birdwatching. This type of farming can take advantage of government programs to improve habitat, generate profit, and provide educational opportunities.

Culture, in many ways, shapes and dictates the dynamics of any negotiation. It's a complex tapestry woven with threads of shared beliefs, traditions, and behaviors that can vary widely between and even within groups. A culture is not merely a homogenous entity; it's a multifaceted entity that can be understood just as much by what it is not as by what it is. Generalizations like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating" oversimplify cultural nuances and can be misleading. While broad generalizations about a culture can be useful, a successful negotiator must understand the specific cultural context and how it influences the negotiation process.

When engaging with a foreign culture, one often compares it to their own, leading to inevitable comparisons. This understanding can be gained through studying its history, customs, and even its biases. Instead of attempting to change or judge a culture, a negotiator should accept it for what it is and navigate it, especially when they hold a weaker position at the table. Respect for local traditions and beliefs can help in overcoming cultural barriers and advancing negotiations.

It's also crucial to recognize that culture isn't confined to national borders. Companies within the same nation can have distinct corporate cultures. For instance, one company might prioritize long working hours while another prefers a more flexible schedule. Signs of corporate culture can be seen in employee attire, communication styles (direct versus indirect), and hiring practices. Some companies encourage philanthropy from employees, while others restrict it to approved causes. These differences can be as pronounced within the United States as they are across different regions and urban/suburban environments.

Values are especially important to understand as they provide the 'why' behind a culture. If a culture values 'saving face' or 'communal harmony,' a negotiator will be cautious about publicly shaming an opponent to secure a deal. Similarly, if a culture values a hard-driven bargain, negotiations might be more tenacious. Knowing these values beforehand can significantly impact a negotiator's approach. However, understanding the personal background of the opposing negotiator can further enhance the effectiveness of the negotiation.

The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’ This sentiment is first seen in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible and is the foundation for St. Anselm’s argument regarding the existence of God. Similarly, this view is held by another author, Thomas Aquinas, who also defends this belief. Given our task is to compare these arguments, we must, for simplicity, assume they are both correct in their belief in God, specifically the God of the Bible. To contrast, we would not be able to compare their arguments effectively if we included a different type of God.

While both authors present valid points, neither truly offers a comprehensive basis for belief in God. We will first examine St. Anselm’s argument. Anselm suggests that understanding God lies within one’s own mind, and that the proof for God is found by examining what we inherently know to be true. He implies that external evidence is unnecessary for this proof, which is often referred to as faith.

Thomas Aquinas, on the other hand, argues that God’s existence can be proven through reason and empirical evidence, negating the need for faith. This approach is beneficial for evangelism as it allows for logical persuasion of new converts without relying on their willingness to accept unprovable truths. Aquinas presents five logical arguments: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. Each argument demonstrates that the proof of God exists in the logical necessity of God.

Around the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince, who would later be known as Buddha, was born. Throughout his life, he abandoned the world and attained enlightenment, leading to the creation of Buddhism, with the most conservative branch being Theravada Buddhism. This religion emerged about 2500 years ago and has evolved significantly over time. For example, in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. Monks and laypeople alike participate, though Buddha never taught about such a festival. These changes span from superficial traditions to the heart of the religion itself. Over time, the Theravada Buddhist community, both from the monastic and lay perspectives, has modified its core beliefs due to various internal and external factors, some hostile and others benign.

Some key terms we'll use often include internal versus external forces. Internal forces are those originating from within the Buddhist community, regardless of monastic status. External forces are from non-Buddhists. Hostile forces are those that harm or intend to harm the Buddhist community, often driven by a negative view of Buddhism. Benign forces do not intend to harm or help the community, but may still do so. These terms will appear frequently in this discussion.

First, let's explore the basics of the religion—its core doctrines. Buddhists find refuge in the Three Jewels: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is composed of the Tripitaka, the three baskets of Buddhist scripture. The Sutta Pitaka includes all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka outlines rules for conduct, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka covers the religion's metaphysical aspects. Key metaphysical concepts include Anatta (no-self), Dukkha (inherent suffering), and Anicca (impermanence). Recognizing these concepts allows one to escape Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth. Along with this, lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion) will cease when one becomes enlightened. The Vinaya Pitaka provides rules for laypeople and monks. Laypeople follow five key precepts: I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not engage in sexual misconduct, and I shall not consume intoxicating substances. Monks have many more rules to adhere to. The core doctrinal notion is the Four Noble Truths: First, that life is full of suffering (Dukkha). Second, that attachment causes suffering. Third, that suffering can be overcome.

The United States of America and Mexico once shared a longstanding rivalry that lasted 57 years, from 1836 to 1893 (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145). The height of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the United States successfully defeated Mexico and gained Texas and the American Southwest as new territories. There were numerous other skirmishes between the two nations, with tensions easing before the First World War.

This is not unique to the United States and Mexico. Many neighboring nations face similar rivalries due to shared borders. David M. Pletcher (1977) points out that "only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting, overarching American diplomatic problems" (p. 41). Both Mexico and Cuba are geographically close to the United States and have historically been rivals, unlike other Latin American nations which have maintained good relations.

Religious differences were a significant source of tension, a problem many nations have faced throughout history. Sally Frahm (2001) notes that in the 18th and 19th centuries, Americans opposed Catholicism and monarchy, similar to the ideological struggles of the Cold War between the United States and the Soviet Union (p.86). This distrust was inherited from the English and Spanish colonial rulers, making amiable foreign relations difficult to establish.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 disputes during this 57-year period. Most of these involved territorial issues, including border raids from Mexican territory and other frontier problems. Bandits and outlaws from American border towns were a significant issue until both countries exerted military force on their borders (Schmitt 1974 p. 97).

Schmitt (1974) explains that the rivalry began to ease as Mexico became significantly dependent on the United States and finally ended as American ambitions shifted from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico in the later part of the 19th century (p. 109-110).

Fifteen years ago, I found myself unexpectedly disabled by an ailment I had never heard of. As a nurse at the time, I had chosen my profession to find the security I lacked as a child. "You'll always be able to find work; people will always get sick" was the mantra I repeated to myself. Despite my dream to be a scientist or journalist, perhaps a bit of both, I chose nursing. Now, here I am—46, single, with no savings and unable to work. I've been living on Social Security Disability for 15 years, and now I have nothing left to call my own. Every day is a struggle, an assault on my security, safety, and self-esteem. Nothing is certain anymore, yet there is one truth: I couldn't have survived these years without my family and a few kind friends. When disaster strikes, no matter how strong you are, you don't feel strong at all.

Life is full of emergencies, big and small. No matter how well-prepared, some are too big to handle alone. We in the U.S. should stop relying solely on big government. Instead, we should learn to trust and help each other. The Conservatives talk about rugged individualism, but our forefathers' success was built on compassion, mutual respect, and shared resources. Pioneers crossing the Rockies didn't make it alone.

Be prepared, I am. I have a disaster kit, first aid, water purification, plastic sheeting, duct tape, flashlights, batteries, candles, matches, and canned goods. If you have the resources and land for a small farm, and can preserve your food, do it. But also, get to know your neighbors.

Why do organisms evolve in the manner that they do? Are there constraints that guide the course of evolutionary change? While D'Arcy Thompson, in 1917, mused that "Even now the zoologist has scarce begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms," this sentiment still holds true today. Recent studies have applied mathematical modeling to various aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis, both ontogenetically and phylogenetically (e.g., Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our investigation explores how combining mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic changes in Prunum, along with experimental studies, can elucidate the mechanisms driving evolutionary-developmental shifts. We used X-radiographic images of Prunum species to identify quantitative parameters, which were then modeled using the software program CerioShell (Stone, 1995). We created hypothetical shell morphologies to interpret the limits of possible morphological changes in Prunum. These results are being integrated with experimental and descriptive studies to better understand macroevolutionary events in this group.

A shell can be visualized as a tube that evolves through 360 degrees of space over time. These 360-degree turns are called whorls, which spiral around an imaginary central axis known as the columella. This columella runs through the central column of the shell. The rate at which whorls enlarge can vary, with a continuous line separating each whorl called a suture. Typically, the largest whorl of a shell is the last one, referred to as the body whorl. The spire is all the whorls except the last. The apex is the tip of the spire, while the base is the opposite end. The animal exits its shell through an opening known as the aperture.

Shells can be examined from apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural views. The "usual" orientation is an apertural view, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing upwards.

To count whorls, first view the shell from the apical perspective and determine where the first suture begins. Draw a line dividing the shell into two parts, then count the whorls from this line, estimating to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be seen as a series of apertures that evolve through time and space as the animal builds its shell. The trajectory of the aperture can be tracked using the coordinates of each whorl's aperture center, as well as its horizontal and vertical radius.

This trajectory can be represented graphically and mathematically. Once a mathematical formulation is established, parameters can be varied and modified to alter the mollusk's skeletogenesis.

The neonatal and infant mortality rates in Indonesia have not seen significant improvement over the past decade. Despite the country's progress towards several Millennium Development Goals, including water and sanitation targets, the progress in child and maternal health lags behind the 2015 goal. Reasons for this include inefficiencies in healthcare delivery and access issues. Indonesia has made strides in the number of births attended by skilled workers, with 72% meeting this target, but it includes traditional workers like midwives who lack medical intervention capabilities, which contributes to high maternal death rates. Additionally, there has been a decline in professional treatment of diarrhea cases in children under five, and postnatal care remains a concern with low rates nationwide. C-section rates remain low, at 4%, with urban rates at 7% and rural at 2%, highlighting healthcare disparities. There is also a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles, indicating that the poor struggle more with healthcare access due to out-of-pocket costs.

In considering how to address these issues, the primary question is whether Indonesia should focus on program-specific solutions or strengthen its overall healthcare system. While targeted programmatic approaches can yield faster results and have clear objectives, they may divert resources from other areas and lead to duplicated, uncoordinated services. For instance, heavy investment in HIV/AIDS programming has negatively impacted family planning efforts. Therefore, a balanced approach that addresses both the immediate challenges and the broader healthcare system is likely necessary.

Victorian novels are known for their meticulous attention to detail and their focus on the aristocracy of the era. Yet, two notable exceptions are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, which break from this mold with their mysterious elements and unique flair. Both works reveal the characters' inner selves, their pains, and their true nature, through these mysterious aspects, which are often depicted through dream sequences or dreamlike states. For instance, in Oliver Twist, such occurrences unveil insights into Oliver's inner turmoil, his awareness of his surroundings, and his lack of control over his fate. When Oliver relives the shooting vividly in chapter 28, it is as if he is in a dream, highlighting his inability to influence the events unfolding around him. The shooting is depicted as overwhelming, numbing his senses and leaving him with constant, dreadful pain linked to fear, rather than surprise. This dreamlike scene underscores Oliver's helplessness and the growing sense of defeat that he has been forced to accept, perhaps by the influence of Fagin. This reinforces the notion that Oliver has little control over his own destiny. The passage also hints at a deeper mystery, raising questions about who or what caused his misfortune, as it was clearly not his own doing. This sequence emphasizes Oliver's inability to regain control of his life, even when it is on the line.

A couple of years ago, I was working in an after school program tutoring Elementary age students. I did my best to assist them in their subjects, but my strengths were in English and reading. A fellow instructor recruited me to help a young boy named Adrian, who was having trouble reading. It was clear that something was off; he could pronounce some letters correctly, while others he got completely wrong, which was puzzling. Adrian was of Latino descent and spoke perfect English, but his reading was a struggle. We kept working on it until I met his mother during a babysitting session. She didn't speak a word of English, only Spanish. Despite my limited Spanish, we managed to communicate. It dawned on me then: Adrian could read fine, he just didn't know the English alphabet very well. I'm not sure if my realization helped him much, but I hope he's doing better now. I share this story to highlight the language barrier in schools, especially in California, and to illustrate that it's not always as apparent as we think. Even for a child who speaks perfect English, reading can still be challenging. The problem is widespread, so what can we do? In Adrian's case, the solution was straightforward: tutoring in English reading, particularly the alphabet and pronunciations. However, for many children who barely speak English, the solution is much more complex. There's no single answer. The dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes—none of these alone will solve the problem. The key is to combine all these methods!

From our childhood, many of us are taught that there's something greater than ourselves, something we can't grasp. Some of us are brought to Sunday school, while others visit temples or search within ourselves for understanding. Some readily accept the beliefs passed down by our parents, while others reject them, denying there's anything beyond our self-centered universe. We may switch our values over time, but whatever path we take, we seek to define ourselves through our unique spiritual views. We search for a guiding light in the darkness to bring us into the sun.

"A cardinal," my father said, when I asked for his favorite bird. We were on the porch, watching the rain smash against the tin roof as we smoked. The gutters sent the rain down, drowning the plants near us. He stared into the rain, a mix of searching and remembering. He'd grown thin, his clothes loose, hair sparse. He avoided my gaze. I felt alone, afraid, unable to discuss his passing. I hugged him, sat back, moved closer, and joined him in watching the rain fall. My father passed in December, five days after my twenty-second birthday. Chemo and radiation prolonged his suffering, but only by a few months. I couldn't watch him leave this life. I chose to remember him by how he lived, not how he died. I curled up in my bed for three days, waiting for news. No one called.

The classic "Gothic Novel," as Ian Watt puts it in "The Rise of the Gothic Novel," is an 'oxymoron for 'Old-New,'" blending the old and the new in both form and substance. The Gothic genre has been both celebrated and critiqued, praised for its 'terrible sublime' and lambasted for lacking depth (Burke). Walpole's "The Castle of Otranto" pioneered the Gothic genre by fusing older theatrical elements and modern literary techniques. It presented a new kind of storytelling that combined the 'old' and the 'new,' idealizing the past while offering a fresh perspective. The term 'Gothic' was used for different peoples, styles, and time periods, often seen as archaic or unsophisticated compared to the 'modern' advancements of literature and society. The Gothic's enduring appeal lies in its unique blend of theatricality and the novel's personal character exploration. Chivalry, a medieval concept, is a key theme in Gothic novels like "The Castle of Otranto," embodying the ideal of a brave, honorable knight. Walpole, writing during a politically fraught time, may have seen a loss of the moral 'goodness' and innate 'goodness' represented by chivalry in his contemporary society. This is seen clearly in characters like Frederic, who exemplifies chivalric traits and is a romanticized ideal of a knight. Walpole's description of Frederic as a prince who has suffered tragedy and is assumed dead by infidels embodies this trope, with his gallant and courteous nature exaggerated to fit the Gothic trope of excess (66).

Supply chain management refers to the sequence of processes that move goods from the point of customer order through raw materials, production, distribution, and finally to the customer. This concept was coined in 1982 by consultant Keith Oliver, who described it as a comprehensive process for planning, implementing, and controlling the supply chain to meet customer needs swiftly and efficiently. There are six pivotal components to a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers leverage these components to deliver exceptional customer service.

Adolf Hitler, it seems, is alive and well in Burma, according to a sign held by Ellen Page, the star of Juno. Burma, or Myanmar as it's known, is a Southeast Asian country under the grip of a ruthless military junta that seized power through a coup in 1962. In 2007, a series of street protests, dubbed the "Saffron Revolution," erupted, led by monks. The protests initially saw peaceful gatherings, but escalated into violence as the military responded with force, invading monasteries and imprisoning foreign journalists, including a Japanese photojournalist named Kenji Nagai who was killed during a protest. Estimates of the death toll range from 13 to several thousand. This is not an isolated incident; throughout history, many regimes have sought to quash dissent and maintain total control. Egyptian pharaohs, Japanese emperors, and even our current president, George W. Bush, have been accused of such actions. Notable examples include the 1989 Tiananmen Square protests, the Rwandan genocide, and Adolf Hitler's 'Third Reich'.

Duke Ellington’s influence on jazz can be attributed to his longevity and the way he crafted his orchestra. His piano presence is often subtle, but as a composer, Ellington excelled, writing intricate pieces that highlighted individual band members' skills. He created a framework for soloists to improvise freely, while also writing tightly orchestrated sections and phrases tailored to each player's unique style. This approach allowed him to emphasize the overall tone of the orchestra, creating cohesive and original sounds for each piece. Ellington’s ability to master individual players' sounds and how they worked together in a growing ensemble led to some of the most innovative and brilliant works in jazz history.

The Grove Music Dictionary highlights Ellington's innovative use of voice as an instrument. This is evident in Creole Love Call, where voice and reeds engage in a call and response, showcasing Ellington's talent for adding texture and color. The piece features a series of choruses, each with distinct soloists and orchestrations. The first chorus has a smooth, melodic voice transitioning to a rougher sound. The second features a muted trumpet solo elaborating on the basic melody with extended blue notes. A sweeping clarinet solo in the third chorus is backed by subtle syncopated piano. The fourth chorus has the full band echoing the first with a call and response by brass and reeds. The fifth chorus is climactic, with reeds in a high register and syncopated stop time from brass and rhythm sections. The sixth chorus returns to the first chorus' structure but with the voice using the "growl" technique. A vocal run and dissonant trombone ending complete the piece.

Ellington’s voice-as-instrument technique is a recurring stylistic trait throughout his work. In Hot and Bothered, recorded a year later, Ellington combines tight orchestration with tone color. A call and response between Bubber Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing uses vocal elements of Miley’s playing and instrumental aspects of Cox’s voice to create a rich sound. It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing) builds on this, with Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton introducing the melody on muted trombone.

She'd always felt an insatiable longing for something, a desire that hadn't been met. It began when she turned 14, just embracing her teenage life, and lingered into her 17th year. She'd come to realize she craved a person, not an item, but her interest in boys remained absent despite some being drawn to her. She puzzled over this strange condition, wondering what could ignite such an unusual reaction in a teenage girl. Despite years of contemplation, she found no definitive answers. So, she carried on, continually questioning her longing.

A typical day at home was usually serene. Her parents were gentle and harmonious, never engaging in arguments with each other or their daughter. The only disputes were about her asserting her independence and vibrant personality, which made her quite likable. Her parents were as calm as could be, but she countered their energy with her lively spirit.

Today was far from calm. As she meandered through the house, seeking inspiration for herself, she heard a sudden cry from the kitchen. Her mother's melodic voice echoed with pain. She rushed in, asking, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" She found her mother on the floor, writhing in discomfort. "Ow... sweet - ty, I ... need you to take me - to the hospital," her mother gasped. She rushed to her side, offering assistance. "Okay, Mom, I'll pick you up. Tell me where." Her mother directed her to the car, and she carried her mother, grateful for her strength, to the vehicle.

The hospital was filled with antiseptic and tension, but her mind was solely focused on helping her mother. She rushed her in and called for help. Doctors quickly gathered and wheeled her mother to the examination area, leaving her to worry.

Her mother had fallen from a step stool while reaching for a vase in the highest cabinet.

This study aimed to demonstrate that sticking to a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), as indicated by a high "alternate Mediterranean diet score" (aMed), is linked to a lower risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, as well as reduced stroke mortality. The aMed diet is a tweaked version of the Med diet, featuring increased consumption of plant foods, including plant proteins (but excluding potatoes, and including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (compared to saturated fats), and fish, along with decreased intake of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol consumption is also allowed.

Previous studies have shown that adhering to a Med diet is inversely associated with the risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality, and it was found to be more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and lowering the total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol ratio among obese individuals. However, these studies did not focus on stroke or stroke mortality.

This epidemiological research tracked 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63, with no history of CVD or diabetes, who are participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. Every six years from 1984 to 2004, the authors calculated an aMed diet score using self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) designed to assess nutrient intake over the preceding year. More than 95% of the nurses continued participating throughout the 20-year period. FFQs underwent validation studies. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed through medical or hospital records, autopsy, or death certificates. In cases where records were unavailable, cases were considered "probable" and included, with around 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts thus classified. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and use of postmenopausal hormones were calculated for each FFQ, and beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed.

To minimize random variation for an individual and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging scores from two prior years). Adjustments were made for "confounders" (factors that could mislead results) by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to examine the association between an aMed score and risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as indicated by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women. Over 20 years of follow-up, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were found. Women in the top aMed quintile had lower risks for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States of America faced a severe financial meltdown. Unemployment surged, the housing market tanked, and several major corporations were left in shambles. We must ponder: how did this catastrophe unfold, and how can we prevent it from happening again? In essence, the crisis was created by selfish and naive political choices that pressured banks and corporations into issuing sub-prime loans to an underdeveloped and insufficient financial system. Concurrently, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were coerced to underwrite and repack these mortgages into CDO’s and CDS’s. When borrowers defaulted, the banks lacked capital reserves and transferred this turmoil onto the repacked mortgages they’d sold, and onto the broader economy.
The origins of this crisis can be traced back to 1999, during the Clinton administration's drive for a second term. To boost his popularity, Clinton relaxed lending restrictions, paving the way for the sub-prime crisis seven years later. Steven Holmes of the New York Times in 1999 warned, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest mortgage underwriter, is under pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand loans to low and moderate-income individuals while feeling the pressure from shareholders to maintain its impressive profit growth.” Holmes accurately predicted the consequences: “But the government-subsidized corporation may face trouble in an economic downturn, requiring a government rescue similar to the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As foreshadowed, imprudent lending led to the economic collapse.
Several factors contributed to the economic nosedive, one being the novel and intricate mortgage structures. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and CDO’s were widely used leading up to the crisis, further entangling the economy with the housing market. This over-leveraging left households and financial markets highly susceptible to even minor price fluctuations.
Eventually, the housing bubble burst, leaving financial institutions that bought these mortgage-backed securities in disarray. The top five U.S. investment banks reported $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts in 2007, representing about 30% of the USA’s GDP. Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold at a discount, Lehman Brothers was dissolved, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were compelled to become commercial banks under intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie, with $5 trillion in mortgage debt, were placed under government control in September 2008.

Exposition, that tricky beast, can be both your friend and foe in storytelling. It's where you dip your toes into the story, setting the stage or laying the groundwork for the adventure to come. Or, it's where your readers might lose interest and hit that "Back" button, cursing your name.

Dr. Merlin, our resident writing expert, has her own beef with exposition—when it's too much, it can be a snoozefest. She's had times where she's shouted at her monitor during those long passages where nothing happens, or where every minute detail of a character's life is laid out like an infomercial.

Exposition is the process of sharing information with the audience about what has happened or is going on. It's like the character who tells another character a detailed history, like in "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner." In fiction, the author is the one doing the storytelling.

Consider this: you're reading a story where the heroine meets her beloved at a specific place and time, they wed in a grand affair, and then her husband is brutally murdered in front of her. The story takes pages to get to this point, and both characters barely speak. You'd expect more than that; you'd want to see how deeply they love each other, how his presence has transformed her life. You'd want to know about his mannerisms, his dreams, his hopes, and how his death impacts her.

In essence, you want meat on the bones of the story, not just a list of events: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, it's your job to provide that substance. It's tempting to rush over certain details, like introducing a new character who used to be in the Air Force, now runs a gas station, was married twice, loves fishing, and dreams of owning the station someday. While these details can be useful, they shouldn't be dumped all at once. Show us why these details matter, and how they shape the character and the story.

I caught two news reports from Columbus, Ohio. The first was NBC 4, which aired live this morning on August 13, 2011. The top story was about a man named Shad Hostettler who had stabbed his wife, though they didn't mention her name. They showed his mug shot, and he looked menacing. This story got about two minutes of coverage, which seemed fitting for its developing nature. The next report was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, an 18-year-old who was critically injured in the Sharon Woods area. No arrests had been made yet, and the SWAT Team was investigate. This story seemed brief, possibly due to racial bias. I've long noticed that minorities often get less coverage when they're crime victims compared to white victims. The following story was about a bullet hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter, caused by a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle. Crime-Stoppers was offering a $5,000 reward for tips leading to the shooter's arrest. There was also a story about rain and thunderstorms expected for Saturday afternoon, with temperatures expected to stay in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. They devoted a short amount of time to this, perhaps as a teaser to keep viewers tuned in. Another story was about a robbery at a Clime Road UDF, with a dark-skinned black man as the suspect. He was described as about six-foot tall and weighing around 150 pounds. They spent an unusual amount of time emphasizing his race and appearance. There was also a story about a convicted drug kingpin named Rene Rodriguez, who had conspired to distribute marijuana from Texas to Ohio. Instead of saying he was sentenced to 25 years, they said "300" months, which seemed strange. They also mentioned he was Hispanic, though this detail didn't seem relevant to the story.

There's a bond between brothers, a bond that's unbreakable and irrevocable. This bond is filled with a mix of emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and even cruelty. Brothers understand each other deeply, almost as if they're mirror images of one another. It's during the toughest times that this bond becomes most apparent, showcasing both the good and the bad. When these emotions surface, they come with a heavy price. Part of understanding the emotions that stem from this fraternal connection is coping with the consequences that follow. By looking into a brother's eyes, one sees not just their reflection, but also their true self. Their actions and the outcomes of those actions reveal their genuine character. In "The Scarlet Ibis," two brothers grapple with this theme and the intense emotions it entails. Amidst a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys embark on a doomed journey. In the climax, bitter disappointment and immense pride collide, with only one brother surviving. The theme is conveyed through the direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions, as well as through the narrator's perspective, which delves into the protagonist's complex feelings and his view of the world, factors that heavily influence his actions.

The protagonist’s actions are driven by a single emotion: pride. From their first adventure together to their final, fateful outing, the protagonist harbors resentment towards Doodle. He had envisioned a brother who could learn all his skills, like holding his breath, running, or climbing the vines of Old Woman Swamp. He desired a brother to race to Horsehead Landing and to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn. But Doodle was born with a weak heart, making such activities unlikely. This dash of reality crushed the protagonist's dreams. Anger even brewed within him, as he contemplated suffocating Doodle with a pillow. Who could harbor such thoughts? Yet, his heart softened when Doodle smiled at him, instilling hope. This showed that his conviction wasn't strong. Deep down, he loved his brother.

The brain, a marvel of complexity, is a creative information processor. As technology evolved from primitive to modern, so too did the metaphors used to describe it. Initially, it was likened to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and now, most recently, to a computer. Keep in mind that while these metaphors are useful, they also have limitations and can lead to inaccurate conclusions.

Information processing commences with signals entering through the senses, which convert physical stimuli like touch, heat, sound waves, or light into electrical signals. These signals are repeatedly processed by the brain in top-down and bottom-up ways. For instance, when gazing at an image of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing compiles basic details like color, orientation, and edges to deduce the presence of a box. Top-down processing then uses these findings to speed up recognition, perhaps helping you identify it as a black box instead of a white hole.

Once processed, an attention filter ranks the importance of the signal and determines which cognitive processes should act upon it. For example, while your brain processes every blade of grass as you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. However, you can pick out your name even in a noisy room. This multi-stage processing, with attention modulating the results repeatedly, allows the brain to function efficiently.

For information to be processed, it first needs to be stored. Various types of memory exist, including sensory, working, and long-term. Initially, information is encoded in specific ways suited to each type of stimulus. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally (how the word looks), phonemically (how it sounds), or semantically (what it means). Once encoded, information must be maintained. Some studies suggest that working memory, storing info for about 20 seconds, does so through a brief electrical loop in certain neurons. Long-term memory is believed to be maintained by specific protein structures.

Numerous models attempt to explain how knowledge is organized in the brain, drawing from how people retrieve memories, computer science, and neurophysiology. The semantic network model posits that concepts are represented as nodes linked based on their relatedness. For example, in such a network, “chair” might link to “table,” which could connect to “wooden,” and so forth.

Aldous Huxley takes a critical stand against the impending danger posed by technology and the capitalist system that supports it, as seen in his dystopian novel, Brave New World. The society values collective over individuality and is programmed from birth to prioritize instant gratification over any other pursuit. The people are essentially pawns in a larger scheme, subjected to a single ideology enforced by the World Controller. Through a Marxist lens, one can discern Huxley’s reservations about the rise of such systems. Terms like homogeny and reification, frequently used in Marxism, underscore the critique of emerging economic structures from Huxley's time.

Capitalism is mocked through the Marxist concept of false consciousness, in which the common people are blinded to their true economic relations to other classes. This is due to ideological control over the proletariat and common laborers, evident in the conditioning of citizens in Brave New World. The lower classes, like Deltas and Gammas, have no true agency; hypnopædia instills a desire to consume, spend, and indulge, manipulated by the World Controller. Hegemony, the dominance of one social class over another, is clearly depicted. The lower classes are unaware of this manipulation, truly 'buying into an ideology that supports the structure' (i.e., capitalism and consumerism). The upper classes, born into awareness, do little more than accept their roles, save for a few Alphas or Betas like Bernard. Interactions among social classes further illustrate the perceived oppression of capitalism.

In Brave New World, individual relationships lack depth, with characters often indistinguishable from one another. Perhaps Huxley suggests that the rise of technology and capitalism together strip individuals of their free will and expression. Love and strong emotions don't exist, replaced by superficial interactions, particularly in the way males discuss women based on their physical attributes (like 'pneumatic quality') and females shamelessly share their encounters. Each class's complacence with their status indicates the socioeconomic effects of capitalism. Their unquestioning obedience to their role in society reflects Marxist thoughts on the proletariat, who are falsely reassured of their superiority through consumption and compliance with their peers.

I've been a University Park student for nearly two and a half years, or around four and a half semesters. Navigating campus can be a challenge. My freshman year, I lived in East Halls, the farthest eastward campus residence, close to stadiums and the Bryce Jordan Center. Walking from Stuart Hall to classes in distant places like Willard building could take up to 25 minutes, especially in State College's harsh weather. Talking to an older alum revealed that East Halls used to be isolated by vast tracts of vacant land. Now, those empty spaces are filled with sports fields, new buildings, and apartments. As campus grows, traveling between places becomes tougher. The solution? Bikes. But bikes alone won't help; students must ride them, and the campus must be designed for cyclists. My friend, who resumed biking after a hiatus, found it the only efficient way to get around. Biking, combined with a bit of oatmeal and exertion, covers 30 miles easily. Like many students, I now live off campus, as distant from the center as some dorms. My smartest decision this year was buying a bike. Daily classes at Thomas building, a 25-minute walk from home, now take just 5 minutes on a bike. The catch? Pollock Road, the direct route, isn't always bike-friendly. While walking has its merits, I'm too busy to walk. Without a bike, walking would be my only option, adding 30-40 minutes to my daily routine, or over two and a half hours weekly. Add to that time spent walking to other classes and appointments, and it's more time than I can afford.
